{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598133"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:32:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:32:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15442"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15442"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.26,0.12,0.14,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69815"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8133"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15442"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55271"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5773"},{"type":"tags","id":"6903"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19715"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19719"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69815"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBacterial peritonitis occurs when microorganisms contaminate the peritoneal cavity, most commonly due to gastrointestinal perforation. The condition can range from localised infection to severe sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements best describes the pathophysiology of bacterial peritonitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The size of bacterial inoculum affects mortality","Gram-positive organisms are the most common cause","Anaerobic bacteria cannot survive in peritoneal fluid","Formation of abscesses indicates treatment failure","The omentum plays no role in containing infection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn bacterial peritonitis, the initial bacterial load or \u003Cstrong\u003Einoculum size\u003C/strong\u003E is a critical determinant of patient outcomes and mortality. Higher bacterial loads are associated with worse outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003EGram-positive organisms\u003C/strong\u003E can cause peritonitis, mixed infections with Gram-negative and anaerobic bacteria are more common, particularly in secondary peritonitis from gastrointestinal perforation. \u003Cstrong\u003EAnaerobic bacteria\u003C/strong\u003E readily survive and multiply in the low-oxygen environment of infected peritoneal fluid.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbscess formation\u003C/strong\u003E is a natural progression of the inflammatory response as the body attempts to contain infection, rather than a sign of treatment failure. The greater \u003Cstrong\u003Eomentum\u003C/strong\u003E plays a vital protective role by walling off infection and participating in the immune response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secondary bacterial peritonitis most commonly results from gastrointestinal perforation with spillage of intestinal contents.","The bacterial load (inoculum) at initial infection strongly influences patient outcomes in peritonitis.","Intra-abdominal abscesses are a common complication of peritonitis due to localised infection and inflammatory response."],"references":["Kaiser L, Surawicz CM. Infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea. Best Pract Res Clin Gastroenterol. 2012 Oct;26(5):563-71. doi: 10.1016/j.bpg.2012.11.001. PMID: 23384802Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Hecker A, Reichert M, Reu\u00df CJ, Schmoch T, Riedel JG, Schneck E, Padberg W, Weigand MA, Hecker M. Intra-abdominal sepsis: new definitions and current clinical standards. Langenbecks Arch Surg. 2019 May;404(3):257-271. doi: 10.1007/s00423-019-01752-7. Epub 2019 Jan 26. PMID: 30685836.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Sell J, Dolan B. Common Gastrointestinal Infections. Prim Care. 2018 Sep;45(3):519-532. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.05.008. Epub 2018 Jul 9. PMID: 30115338"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55271"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15442"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55271"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T19:57:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T19:57:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8133"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69815"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"ta